text: ¬†@Nambark¬† ¬†I'm going to apologize out front, I am rather frustrated at your comments about musical groups. I have nothing to say about streaming or success, and I'm sorry to awaken this after a year or more, but I have a problem about being angry over anything, and the lack of understanding about professional  music, while not complete, is a little frustrating. Your primary arguments about many people in Hololive not having to be very talented is incorrect. You stated your experience in a church choir as proof that you have enough knowledge to be able to say something on the subject. I admit that many people have talent, many including yourself, however a professional choral group is on another level. A professional group meets daily and practices outside of group practice and rehearsal, this is their way of gaining a living, it is not something they take lightly. While again, I am no authority on the subject, I believe at least some of these V-tubers fall into that category. In respond to that other comment you made about multiple groups learning music in a language that isn't their own, you have not given a solid piece of evidence, either a name for the group/groups, or a link to the video or article that gave you this knowledge. Without that, it is simply hearsay. As an example, one member of Pentetonix, who's name escapes me, made multiple references in an interview about practicing on their own and then hoping, and working on syncing their practice and parts with the rest of the group. This isn't the best example as I don't have a link on hand of either an interview or the video I saw, but I believe it was a winter collaboration with a choir from Brigham Young University, but I may be mistaken. I am certain you will not read all of this, if you do, kudos, if you don't, fair enough. I again apologize for bringing this up, and my experience with choir is not all that extensive, only four years of high school musicals and jazz choirs, and a couple experiences in a church choir. And your comment about a church choir is very accurate, although some of the more musically inclined probably practiced on their own time a bit. This is just my two cents though, so whatever, thank you for letting me vent, I needed it

This entire stream was amazing. :_GuraLove:

Deciding to do a Hololive karaoke for your 2 mil celebration stream is perfect. Not only do you get to keep the archive by only singing songs from other Hololive members, but you also get to promote those members in a stream that many people will watch. Its a perfect way to celebrate this huge milestone while also celebrating Hololive as a whole. ‚ñ°
You deserve all of the support that you have and all that has happened to you since debut.  You might be an awkward person who ends up fumbling your way through many things but you are also a genuinely amazing person who is very talented and know how capture the hearts of many people. When you're not feeling well or up to it to stream, don't feel bad about not streaming. We understand if you need to take some time for yourself and we will wait as long as needed for you come back, full of energy.

text:
It is very touching to see just how much it means for Gura to sing. It is not just a talent or hobby for her. It genuinely is a form of expression - the one she knows best in place of words, and her personal way of saying "thank you" as well, which is why she chose karaoke for her celebration stream. I am not a musical person myself, but just hearing her and seeing how meaningful this is for her actually lowkey inspires me to at least try singing once in my life before I die, something I am usually adamantly against. I was at first not going to watch this live, but randomly stopping by and staying for all the songs has been the best decision I have taken in who knows how long now.

Thank you, Gura, and congratulations. You are living the very best years of your life, and now, I am inspired to do the same, no matter what it takes, how unlikely it is or how long. Just you watch.

¬†@justinrald3318¬† Possibly.

When you strike a Youtube video, you immediately get the Ad income from that video, and you don't have to pay it back even when the dispute is resolved.

That's why lots of those lawyers blindly issue strikes whenever the ContentID tool tell them a video matches and could be copyright violation, even when the tool now also explicitly say the user should verify themselves - they really have all to gain and nothing to lose by striking the wrong person.
